entry.title: Update WindowPreviewView subtree's rounded corners to avoid render
entry.content:
surfaces.



A recent change, b/40245439, now does not create render surface if

a rounded layer subtree fits withing the bounds of the rounded layer.

This change works great but is troublesome if a child layer rounded

corner overlaps with the parent layer rounded corner. Since Skia

renderer can only handle one rounded corner per each quad, we get

visual artifacts as in the case of WindowPreviewView with rounded

windows.



In WindowPreviewView, the preview_view (holding the mirrored content)

has rounded corners. But the mirrored layers, which are children of

WindowPreviewView can have rounded corners of their own. Iconically,

the mirrored layers rounded corners overlaps with WindowPreviewView

rounded corners causes visual artifacts. (See b/313517052)



Easy solution is to create a render surface but in the case of

WindowPreviewView, it is expensive as seen in the regression,

b/316018723. The temporary fix was to create render surfaces only

if rounded windows is enabled but the regression will come back if

rounded windows feature is enabled.



In this CL, we update the radii of overlapping corners of the

layers in the subtree rooted at WindowPreviewView such that

both the overlapping corners have the same radii. This gets rid

of the visual artifacts without the need of render surfaces.



Bug: b/326468096, b/316018723, b/313517052

Currently, we use the helper method chromeos::GetWindowCornerRadius()

to get the radius of window.

`aura::client::kWindowCornerRadiusKey` to get the radius of the window.

drop shadow.



The benefit of this change is that, we can easily control rounding of

window and its decoration thus allowing us to control rounding of

different types of Windows. This behavior is important for exo-based

windows where the client applications can specify their rounding.

entry.title: android: Rename MessagePumpForUI as MessagePumpAndroid
entry.content:
This is a followup to crrev.com/1270888. Currently there is only one

MessagePump class in use for Android (outside testing), and it is called

MessagePumpForUI. There is no plan to create more MessagePump classes

for Android. Though as the interfaces diverges, it would be nicer to

give the Android messagepump a distinct name, if only for easier

grep-ability.



For consistency, the testing class is also renamed: MessagePumpForUIStub

-> MessagePumpAndroidStub.



The next followup would be to change the popular constructor of the

entry.title: [ash] Ensure nested DisplayManager changes are ordered correctly
entry.content:
Currently it is possible for DisplayManager observers to trigger

further synchronous DisplayManager changes during change event

propagation. This nested behavior can result in change

notifications being delivered to observers out of order.



A concrete example of where this is currently happening is in

b/327282654. This occurs as follows.



1. A Display is added and DisplayManager begins notifying

observers of the added Display

2. One of the observers updates the insets of the added Display

3. DisplayManager now notifies observers of the inset change

4. DisplayManager notifies the remaining observers of the

original added Display



As a result the later observers receive DisplayManager changes

out of order and invariants fail.



This CL addresses this issue for DisplayManagerObservers. A

BeginEndNotifier is created when propagating notifications so

that these can be correctly sequenced after all observers have

been notified of the original change.



The change preserves the "will process" and "did process" observer

sequencing for a given change. This is not ideal given this is

propagated after the DisplayManager has actually updated its state,

howevever preserving this sequencing seems better than delivering

multiple "will process" events followed by multiple "did process"

events.



A more correct and robust fix for this behavior will be explored in

the resolution of b/328134509.

entry.title: [ios] Do not drop form mutations bundled together; relax throttle
entry.content:
We've observed that in some sign-in uff flows, the password form

isn't detected.



This is because the added form mutation used as the signal to detect

the new form is bundled in the same mutation payload as the removed

username form. As there can't be more than one message scheduled at a

time (for throttling), the added form event is dropped hence

doesn't make it to the browser to parse the new form.



Here we propose to relax throttling a little bit when an added form

mutation and a removed form mutation are bundled together. Up to 2

messages can be scheduled at the same time while keeping a delay

between both.



Other messages will still be skipped if there is already a scheduled

message.

entry.title: Android: Remove occurrences of JavaRef<jclass>
entry.content:
jclass objects should always come JNI Zero's from generated _clazz()

methods, which use base jclass. Having APIs that use non-bare jclass

makes these methods hard to use.



Why not just use JavaRef<> instead of bare jclass? Because the

_clazz() use std::atomic to store them, and there is no

way to return a JavaRef<> from a jclass without going through

ScopedJavaLocalRef, which adds an unnecessary local ref.



The change:

1) Changes JavaRef in jni_array.cc to use bare jclass,

and updates all call sites to them as well.



When it was straight-forward, I updated call sites to use @JniType

instead of manual vector->array conversions.



This changes @JniType support in three ways:

1) Automatically add the template type for @JniType("std::vector")

(usually ScopedJavaLocalRef).

2) Add jni_zero::ConvertArray specialization for

ScopedJavaLocalRef.

3) When returning a typed array for a non-system type, pass the

Class object as the last parameter.

* This is a bit subtle, but it nice because it will allow R8 to

rename the class that is being used.

* We unfortunately cannot use this trick for @CalledByNative

parameters, so should likely emit a warning / error if

application array types are used in this context.

entry.title: [//components/exo] Compute texture target to use from ClientSharedImage
entry.content:
exo::Buffer takes in a texture target to use and when in zero-copy mode,

passes it to a gpu::MailboxHolder that it creates. The only production

callsites that create exo::Buffer instances in zero-copy mode are at

[1] and [2] (the latter via [3][4]).



This CL changes exo::Buffer to compute the texture target from the

ClientSharedImage that was created from the passed-in GMB. This

function has identical semantics to what is currently being done, based

on the following reasoning:



* For [1], the texture target is currently being computed at [5]. This

is exactly what ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(BufferFormat)

does.

* [2] is hardcoding the format to RGBA_8888. For RGBA_8888,

ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(BufferFormat) will always return

GL_TEXTURE_2D on ChromeOS [6].



We leave a CHECK_EQ() for verification in going through trybots/CI. Once

this CL passes trybots/CI, we will remove exo::Buffer taking in a

texture

target altogether.

entry.title: [//gpu] Handle 2-fence case in AHBDawnImageRepresentation::EndAccess()
entry.content:
We currently DCHECK() that SharedTextureMemory::EndAccess() gives us

back 1 FD. However, that DCHECK is going off (see bug). On code

inspection, SharedTextureMemoryVk::EndAccessImpl() creates and gives

back 1 FD, while SharedTextureMemory::EndAccess() will add on the FD

that we gave in BeginAccess() if that FD wasn't consumed in a submit

(i.e., Dawn didn't touch the texture during the access).



This CL works around the bug by having

AHBDawnImageRepresentation::EndAccess() restore the fence that was

created in BeginAccess() in this case, as that is still the fence on

which the next access should wait. Once crbug.com/dawn/2454 is fixed,

this Chromium-side special-casing will no longer be necessary, as Dawn

will return the fence passed to it in BeginAccess() as the sole fence

in this case.

entry.title: Fix sandbox top navigation tests using external URLs.
entry.content:
The sandbox top navigation WPTs currently attempt a top-level navigation

to 'https://google.com'. Not only is using external URLs bad practice,

Firefox's test harness code refuses to make requests to remote URLs.

This causes these tests to crash in their trybots.



This CL updates the tests to point to the WPT-supported URL

'http://{{hosts[alt][www2]}}:{{ports[http][0]}}'. This is chosen so the

URL will be cross-site to the URLs the main page and the iframes will

be navigated to in the various tests.



See this comment on the WPT GitHub repo:

https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/35697#issuecomment-1970026245
